{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "phil-mind-expert",
    "senderColor": "orange",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Risk real but small — one TN sentence neutralizes it completely",
    "content": "\n**The risk is real but small, and easily neutralized.**\n\nThe risk is real because scholars DO notice non-standard renderings of canonical passages. It signals \"this person is making their own translation choices\" -- which can read as either confidence or ignorance depending on context.\n\nBut it is small because: (a) \"humaneness\" for 仁 is not idiosyncratic -- it is Ames and Rosemont's standard rendering and is widely used in contemporary scholarship; (b) \"rightness\" for 义 and \"ritual conduct\" for 礼 are similarly within the range of established scholarly options; (c) the author is explicitly not doing sinological exegesis of the Laozi -- the passage is an example for a structural argument. Any scholar who reads the actual analysis will see that immediately.\n\n**Neutralize it completely with one sentence in the TN:** \"The author's translation of this passage departs from standard renderings (cf. Lau, Chan) to maintain terminological consistency with the analysis that follows.\" This signals: the author knows the standard translations, chose to depart for a stated reason, and invites the reader to compare. That is the mark of competence, not ignorance.\n"
  }
}
